04535nam a22006735i 9781478021780DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021011902  a9781478021780  a(DE-B1597)613349  a(OCoLC)1268217239  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aTR848 4aTR848 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a7772231 aDoane, Mary Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBigger Than Life :bThe Close-Up and Scale in the Cinema /cMary Ann Doane. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Scale, the Cinematic Image, and the Negotiation of Space -- tPART I. CLOSE-UP/FACE -- tChapter 1. The Delirium of a Minimal Unit -- tChapter 2. The Cinematic Manufacture of Scale, or Historical Vicissitudes of the Close-Up -- tChapter 3. At Face Value -- tPART II. SCALE/SCREEN -- tChapter 4. Screens, Female Faces, and Modernities -- tChapter 5. The Location of the Image: Projection, Perspective, and Scale -- tChapter 6. The Concept of Immersion: Mediated Space, Media Space, and the Location of the Subject -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Bigger Than Life Mary Ann Doane examines how the scalar operations of cinema, especially those of the close-up, disturb and reconfigure the spectator's sense of place, space, and orientation. Doane traces the history of scalar transformations from early cinema to the contemporary use of digital technology. In the early years of cinema, audiences regarded the monumental close-up, particularly of the face, as grotesque and often horrifying, even as it sought to expose a character's interiority through its magnification of detail and expression. Today, large-scale technologies such as IMAX and surround sound strive to dissolve the cinematic frame and invade the spectator's space, “immersing” them in image and sound. The notion of immersion, Doane contends, is symptomatic of a crisis of location in technologically mediated space and a reconceptualization of position, scale, and distance. In this way, cinematic scale and its modes of spatialization and despatialization have shaped the modern subject, interpolating them into the incessant expansion of commodification.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCinematographyxHistory. 0aDigital cinematography. 0aMotion picture audiencesxPsychology. 0aParticipatory theater. 0aPlace (Philosophy) in motion pictures. 0aSpace in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2021z9783110753790oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishz978311075403208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147802178040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021780423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021780/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075403-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DPKb2021